On Linux
========

* install the following packages through your package manager (following guide
  written for apt-get, tested on Ubuntu 14.10):
  - build-essential
  - python3
  - python3-dev
  - python3-pyqt

* create a virtual environment:
  $ pip install virtualenv
  $ cd /path/to/orange3
  $ virtualenv venv_orange3 --python=python3 --system-site-packages

* activate virtual environment:
  $ source venv_orange3/bin/activate

* install requirements
  $ pip install numpy
  $ pip install -r orange3/requirements.txt
  $ python setup.py develop

* clone CPE & install its dependencies into orange3 venv:
  $ git clone https://github.com/qusp/cpe
  $ pip install -r cpe/requirements.txt

* auto-generate widgets for CPE nodes:
  $ python scripts/regenerate_widgets.py --neuropype-path /your/path/to/cpe
  (you can re-invoke this command whenever you have edited your CPE code)

* for a good development experience, we recommend that you install PyCharm,
  open the orange3 folder with it, and then under
  Settings / Project: orange3 / Project Interpreter / Project Interpreter click the
  gear icon, click Add local..., and select the python executable in your
  orange3_venv/bin folder. Then accept and close the settings dialog.
  Next, click Open, select the cpe directory and accept, and select
  "open in current window" and "add to current project". Now, in the Project
  pane to the left, go to Orange/canvas/__main__.py, right-click and select
  "Create '__main__'". Now in the window that just opened, change the name to
  VPE, and under Script parameters, add: --clear-widget-settings
  Now you can select VPE in the pull-down menu on the top left and either click
  the play button for a normal run or the bug button for a debug run.

